</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="30.[164,779,1470,1584]" box="[164,283,1470,1491]" pageId="30" pageNumber="102">
<emphasis box="[164,283,1470,1491]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="102">Etymology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[164,779,1470,1584]" pageId="30" pageNumber="102">
The Greek epithet ‘ 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ricarte &amp; Marcos-García &amp; Hancock &amp; Rotheray" authorityYear="2012" box="[386,452,1501,1522]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Quichuana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="102" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="melas">
<emphasis box="[386,452,1501,1522]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="102">melas</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
’, means ‘black’ and refers to the absence of bright hairs on the body and the overall dark appearance of this species.
</paragraph>
